---
import TechnologyLayout from '../../layouts/TechnologyLayout.astro';
import TextSection from '../../components/content/TextSection.astro';
import SectionWrapper from '../../components/ui/SectionWrapper.astro';
import WhenToChoose from '../../components/content/WhenToChoose.astro';
---

<TechnologyLayout
  title="Dagster | Nimzo Data"
  description="Dagster orchestration for complex data pipelines — asset-based modeling, data quality checks, and Dagster Cloud deployment on GCP."
  toolName="Dagster"
  toolCategory="Orchestration"
  heroPositioning="Orchestration for when pipelines get complex enough that &ldquo;scheduled to run every morning&rdquo; stops being good enough."
>
  <TextSection title="What It Is" bg="white">
    <p>Dagster is a modern data orchestrator — the tool that sits on top of your pipelines and transformations to schedule them, handle dependencies, retry failures, and give you visibility into what ran, when, and why something broke. It competes with Airflow and Prefect, with a stronger focus on data quality and developer experience.</p>
  </TextSection>

  <TextSection title="Why We Chose It" bg="white">
    <p>Most of our projects don't need orchestration — Airbyte and Dataform both schedule themselves, and for simple stacks adding an orchestrator is over-engineering. When orchestration is genuinely needed (custom scripts with dependencies, complex data quality checks, cross-pipeline coordination), Dagster is the clearest improvement over Airflow. The software engineering quality is noticeably higher, the UI is actually usable, and the asset-based model matches how data teams think about pipelines.</p>
  </TextSection>

  <TextSection title="How We Use It" bg="white">
    <ul class="how-list">
      <li>Orchestrate multi-step custom Python scripts with explicit dependencies and data quality checks between steps</li>
      <li>Define and monitor &ldquo;assets&rdquo; — the actual tables and files your pipeline produces, not just the jobs that build them</li>
      <li>Coordinate dbt Core runs alongside custom pipelines when dbt Cloud's scheduler isn't enough</li>
      <li>Set up Dagster Cloud for managed hosting when clients don't want to maintain GKE infrastructure</li>
      <li>Integrate Dagster alerts with Slack, PagerDuty, or email so failures surface in the tools your team already watches</li>
    </ul>
  </TextSection>

  <SectionWrapper bg="white" py="lg">
    <WhenToChoose
      title="When Dagster is the right orchestrator — and when it isn't"
      blocks={[
        {
          heading: 'Choose Dagster when:',
          bullets: [
            'You have four or more custom pipelines with dependencies',
            'You need data quality checks as first-class pipeline elements',
            'You want the best developer experience in orchestration',
          ],
          note: 'Premium projects — the added complexity justifies premium pricing.',
        },
        {
          heading: 'Choose no orchestrator when:',
          bullets: [
            'Your stack is Airbyte + Dataform + a BI tool',
            'Each tool self-schedules',
          ],
          note: 'This is the right answer for 80% of implementations.',
        },
        {
          heading: 'Choose Cloud Functions + Cloud Scheduler when:',
          bullets: [
            'You have one to three simple scheduled scripts',
            "You don't need dependency management between them",
          ],
          note: 'Free tier handles it, zero maintenance.',
        },
        {
          heading: 'Choose Airflow when:',
          bullets: [
            "You're in an existing Airflow shop",
            "The cost of switching outweighs Dagster's advantages",
          ],
        },
      ]}
      footer="For new projects, Dagster is the better default."
    />
  </SectionWrapper>
</TechnologyLayout>

<style>
  .how-list {
    list-style: disc;
    padding-left: 22px;
    margin: 0;
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  .how-list li { margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .how-list li::marker { color: var(--color-primary); }
</style>
